     <axiom component="lesson-plan">
      <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Suggested Time</title>
          <p>15 minutes</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Objective</title>
          <p>To discover that the product of two square roots is the square root of their product.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Teacher's Role</title>
          <p>Provide pairs of square roots (e.g., <m>\sqrt{4}</m> and <m>\sqrt{9}</m>). Ask learners to find the product of the roots first, then find the root of the product (<m>\sqrt{4 \times 9}</m>). Challenge them to see if this works for non-perfect squares like <m>\sqrt{2}</m> and <m>\sqrt{3}</m> using calculators.</p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>In your groups, investigate the relationship between multiplication and radicals:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Calculate <m>\sqrt{4} \times \sqrt{9}</m>. Now calculate <m>\sqrt{4 \times 9}</m>. Are they the same?</li>
          <li>Using a calculator, find the value of <m>\sqrt{2} \times \sqrt{8}</m>. What is the square root of 16? What does this tell you about <m>\sqrt{2} \times \sqrt{8}</m>?</li>
          <li>Predict the result of <m>\frac{\sqrt{50}}{\sqrt{2}}</m> without a calculator, then check your answer.</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </activity>



